{{redirect-distinguish2|OSCP|[[Online Certificate Status Protocol]] (OCSP)}}
'''Offensive Security Certified Professional''' ('''OSCP''') is an [[White hat (computer security)|ethical hacking]] [[professional certification|certification]] offered by [[Offensive Security]] company that teaches [[penetration testing]] methodologies and the use of the tools included with the [[Kali Linux]] distribution (successor of [[BackTrack]]).<ref>{{cite web| title=Offensive Security Certified Professional| url=https://www.offensive-security.com/information-security-certifications/oscp-offensive-security-certified-professional/ |publisher=Offensive Security |accessdate=13 October 2016}}</ref> The OSCP is a hands-on [[penetration testing]] certification, requiring holders to successfully attack and penetrate various live machines in a safe lab environment.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ethicalhacker.net/columns/linn/final-course-exam-review-pen-testing-with-backtrack |title=Final Course and Exam Review: Pen Testing with BackTrack |author=Linn, Ryan |date=1 March 2010 |publisher=EH-Net Online Mag |accessdate=13 October 2016}}</ref> It is considered more technical than other ethical hacking certifications,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://intelligent-defense.softwareadvice.com/how-to-get-an-ethical-hacker-job-0714/ |title=How to Get a Job as an Ethical Hacker |date=15 July 2014 |last=Westfall |first=Brian |accessdate=13 October 2016 |work=Intelligent Defense |publisher=Software Advice}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.networkworld.com/article/3105496/security/how-well-does-social-engineering-work-one-test-returned-150.html |title=How well does social engineering work? One test returned 150% |last=Dix |first=John |date=11 August 2016 |accessdate=13 October 2016 |publisher=[[Network World]]}}</ref> and is one of the few certifications that requires evidence of practical [[penetration testing]] skills.<ref name=IAnewsletter>{{cite journal |url=https://www.csiac.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Vol15_No2.pdf |title=Certification Spotlight: Offensive Security's OSCP |date=2012 |last=Merritt |first=Chris |journal=IAnewsletter |volume=15 |issue=2 |pages=24-25 |publisher=[[Information Assurance Technology Analysis Center]]}}</ref>
==OSCP course== The course leading up to the OSCP certification was first offered in 2006 under the name "Offensive Security 101". Students expecting a [[101 (term)|101 course]] were not prepared for the level of effort the course requires, so the name was changed to "Pentesting With BackTrack" in December 2008, and again to "Penetration Testing With Kali Linux" when the BackTrack distribution was rebuilt as Kali.<ref name=IAnewsletter />
The course covers common attack vectors used during penetration tests and audit. The course is offered in two formats, either online or live "instructor led" classes. The online course is a package consisting of videos, a PDF, lab assignments and lab access. The instructor led course is intensive live training covering the same material, also with lab access. The labs are accessible via a high speed internet connection, and contain a variety of [[operating system]]s and network devices where the students perform their assignments.
==OSCP challenge== Upon completion of the course students become eligible to take the certification challenge.<ref>{{cite web| title=Information Security Training and Ethical Hacking Courses| url=https://www.offensive-security.com/information-security-training/ |accessdate=13 Oct 2016| publisher=Offensive Security}}</ref> They are given 24 hours in an unfamiliar lab to successfully complete the exam requirements. Documentation must include procedures used and proof of successful penetration including special marker files that are changed per exam. Exam results are reviewed by a certification committee and a reply is given within 72 hours.
==Re-certification== The OSCP does not require re-certification.
== Relations to other security trainings or exams == Successful completion of the OSCP exam qualifies the student for 40 [[(ISC)²]] [[continuing professional development|CPE]] credits.
In 2015, the UK's predominant accreditation body for penetration testing, CREST,<ref>{{cite report |url=http://eprints.lancs.ac.uk/74275/ |title=Analysis and recommendations for standardization in penetration testing and vulnerability assessment: Penetration testing market survey |last1=Knowles |first1=William |last2=Baron |first2=Alistair |last3=McGarr |first3=Tim |date=26 May 2015 |publisher=[[BSI Group]] & [[Lancaster University]]}}</ref> began recognising OSCP as equivalent to their intermediate level qualification CREST Registered Tester (CRT).<ref>{{cite press release|title=CREST Signs New Partnership with Offensive Security to Improve the Standards of Information Security|date=4 August 2015|publisher=CREST and Offensive Security|url=https://www.crest-approved.org/2015/08/04/crest-partnership-with-offensive-security/index.html}}</ref>
